<chapter xml:id="chapter-exp" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Exponential growth</title>

<section xml:id="section-exp-functions">
<title>Exponential functions</title>

<example xml:id="example-exp-doubling">
	<title>A doubling population</title>

	<p>
	An environmental scientist is studying a population of trees in a geographic area
	by making an annual count of individual trees in randomly selected smaller areas and then extrapolating to an estimate for the total population of that type of tree in the entire area.
	She observes that the estimated population size approximately doubles every year.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-exp-doubling-points">
		<caption>
			Data points for population count.
			Note that axes are not the same scale.
		</caption>
		<image width="50%">
			<description> Data points for rate of growth of a population. </description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="exp.d/trees-points.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	To create a mathematical model from the data points,
	the researcher fits a curve to them.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-exp-doubling-curve">
		<caption> Fitted curve for rate of growth of a population. </caption>
		<image width="50%">
			<description> Fitted curve for rate of growth of a population. </description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="exp.d/trees-curve.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<p>
If we assign a scale on both axes in <xref ref="figure-exp-doubling-curve" /> so that the grid lines fall at integer values,
the the plotted points fall at
<md>
	<mrow>
		r(0) \amp = 1 \amp
		r(1) \amp = 2 \amp
		r(2) \amp = 4 \amp
		r(3) \amp = 8 \amp
		r(4) \amp = 16
	</mrow>
</md>,
as the height of each data point is double the height of the preceding point,
in line with the <q>doubling every year</q> observation of the researcher,
and we can model these data points with the formula
<me> q(t) = 2^t </me>.
If we plot some additional points,
we find the fitted curve matches other values of this quantity function.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-exp-base2-more-points">
	<caption>
		Plotting function values <m>q(-1) = 2^{-1}</m> and <m>q(1/2) = 2^{1/2}</m>
		on our <q>doubling</q> model curve.
	</caption>
	<image width="66%">
		<description> Plotting additional function values against our <q>doubling</q> model curve. </description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="exp.d/base2-recip-root.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
It appears that the model curve matches the values of the function <m>q(t) = 2^t</m> not only at whole, positive exponents but also at
<ul>
	<li>
		negative exponents, which are used to mean <term>reciprocal</term>:
		<me> 2^{-a} = \frac{1}{2^a} </me>
	</li>
	<li>
		rational exponents, which are used to combine a power with a root:
		<me> 2^{a/b} = \sqrt[b]{2^a} </me>.
	</li>
</ul>
We are not yet ready to attach a meaning to <em>irrational</em> exponents,
such as <me> 2^{\pi} </me>,
but for the moment we will assume that our formula <m> r(t) = 2^t </m> matches our model curve at <em>all</em> values of <m>t</m>.
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-exp-func">
	<title>Exponential function with base <m>a</m></title>
	<p>
	For positive constant <m>a</m>,
	the function <m>f(t) = a^t</m>.
	</p>
</definition>

<p>
Exponential functions come in three varieties:
<ul>
	<li> exponential growth when <m> a \gt 1 </m> </li>
	<li> constant when <m>a = 1</m> </li>
	<li> exponential decay when <m>0 \lt a \lt 1</m>. </li>
</ul>
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-exp-graphs">
	<caption>Graphs of exponential functions.</caption>
	<sidebyside valign="middle" widths="50% 40%"> <!-- widths="" margins=""  -->
		<figure>
			<caption> A typical exponential growth graph. </caption>
			<image>
				<description> A typical exponential growth graph. </description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="exp.d/generic-growth-graph.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
		<figure>
			<caption> A typical exponential decay graph. </caption>
			<image>
				<description> A typical exponential decay graph. </description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="exp.d/generic-decay-graph.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
	</sidebyside>
</figure>

</section>


<section xml:id="section-exp-basic-props">
<title>Basic properties of exponential functions</title>

<p> From the graphs in <xref ref="figure-exp-graphs" /> we have some obvious properties. </p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-exp-domain-range">
	<title>Domain and range</title>
	<p>
	The domain of an exponential function covers the whole real number line,
	with no singular points,
	and the range consists of all positive real numbers.
	</p>
</identity>

<identity xml:id="pattern-exp-limits">
	<title>Long-term behaviour</title>
	<p><ul>
		<li> <title> Growth </title> <p>
			When <m>a \gt 1</m>, we have
			<me> a^t \to \infty \quad \text{ as } \quad t \to \infty </me>
			and
			<me> a^t \to 0 \quad \text{ as } \quad t \to -\infty </me>.
		</p> </li>
		<li> <title> Decay </title> <p>
			When <m>0 \lt a \lt 1</m>, we have
			<me> a^t \to 0 \quad \text{ as } \quad t \to \infty </me>
			and
			<me> a^t \to \infty \quad \text{ as } \quad t \to -\infty </me>.
		</p> </li>
	</ul></p>
</identity>

<p> The graphs of all exponential functions look essentially the same because they are all horizontal transformations of each other. </p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-exp-horiz-scale">
	<title>Horizontal transformations of exponential graphs</title>

	<statement>

		<p>
		Given two positive bases <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
		the exponential function <m>b^t</m> is a horizontal transformation of the exponential function <m>a^t</m>.
		In particular,
		there exists a number <m>c</m> so that
		<me> b^t = a^{c t} </me>.
		Note that if <m>c</m> is negative,
		this transformation involves not only a horizontal scale but also a reflection.
		</p>

		<aside><title>A look ahead</title><p>
			The horizontal scale factor <m>c</m> in <xref ref="pattern-exp-horiz-scale" /> can be expressed in terms of logarithms,
			as we will see in
			<xref ref="chapter-log" />.
			<!-- a later chapter. -->
			<!-- TODO add to log chapter -->
		</p></aside>

	</statement>

	<proof>

		<p>
		Since the <q>new</q> base <m>b</m> is a positive number,
		it is in the range of the exponential function <m>a^t</m>.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="figure-exp-new-base-on-generic-graph">
			<caption> New base as an output of an exponential function. </caption>
			<image width="66%">
				<description> New base as an output of an exponential function. </description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="exp.d/new-base-on-generic-graph.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p>
		So there is some number <m>c</m> so that <m>a^c = b</m>.
		Substituting this value of <m>b</m> in terms of <m>a</m> and <m>c</m> into the exponential function formula <m>b^t</m>,
		we obtain
		<me> b^t = {(a^c)}^t = a^{c t} </me>.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="figure-exp-new-base-horiz-scale-graph">
			<caption> Graph of one exponential function as a horizontal scaling of another. </caption>
			<image width="66%">
				<description> Graph of one exponential function as a horizontal scaling of another. </description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="exp.d/new-base-horiz-scale-graph.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

	</proof>

</identity>

<remark><p>
	The transformation in <xref ref="pattern-exp-horiz-scale" /> will involve a horizontal reflection precisely when one of the bases is greater than one and the other is less than one.
	That is, when one exponential function is a growth function and the other is a decay function.
</p></remark>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-exp-natural">
<title>The natural exponential function</title>

<subsection>
<title>Euler's number</title>

<p> There exists a particular base for an exponential function that is preferred. </p>

<definition xml:id="definition-exp-euler">
	<title>Euler's number</title>

	<aside>
		<title>Leonhard Euler</title>
		<p> 1707 <ndash /> 1783. </p>
	</aside>

	<p>
	The real number,
	denoted by the letter <m>e</m>,
	so that the area bounded under the graph of <m>f(t) = 1/t</m> over the domain <m>1 \le t \le e</m> is exactly <m>1</m>.
	</p>

</definition>

<figure xml:id="figure-exp-euler">
	<caption> Euler's number defined as an area under <m>f(t) = 1/t</m>. </caption>
	<image width="33%">
		<description> Euler's number defined as creating a specific area under the graph of the reciprocal function. </description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="exp.d/euler.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
Sage knows about Euler's number <c>e</c>.
We can express it as a decimal number using the <c>n()</c> method.
</p>

<sage xml:id="sage-exp-euler-as-number">
	<input>e.n()</input>
	<output>2.71828182845905</output>
</sage>

<p>
The exponential function with base <m>e</m> has a special relationship to the <term>natural logarithm function</term> that we will learn about in
<xref ref="chapter-log" />,
<!-- a later chapter, -->
so it becomes <q>natural</q> to compare every exponential function to the exponential function with base <m>e</m>.
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-exp-natural">
	<title>Natural exponential function</title>
	<p> The function <m>\exp(t) = e^t</m>, where the constant base <m>e</m> is Euler's number. </p>
</definition>

</subsection>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-exp-more-props">
<title>More properties of exponential functions</title>

<p>
Here are some properties of exponential functions.
We will justify these properties
in <xref ref="chapter-log" />.
<!-- in a later chapter. -->
<!-- TODO -->
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-exp-sum">
	<title>Exponential of a sum</title>
	<p>
	For positive base <m>a</m>,
	we have <me> a^{u + v} = a^u a^v </me>.
	In other words, <em>the exponential of a sum is the product of the exponentials</em>.
	</p>
</identity>

<identity xml:id="pattern-exp-negative">
	<title>Exponential of a negative</title>
	<p>
	For positive base <m>a</m>,
	we have <me> a^{- u} = \frac{1}{a^u} </me>.
	In other words, <em>the exponential of a negative is the reciprocal of the exponential</em>.
	</p>
</identity>

<identity xml:id="pattern-exp-diff">
	<title>Exponential of a difference</title>
	<p>
	For positive base <m>a</m>,
	we have <me> a^{u - v} = \frac{a^u}{a^v} </me>.
	In other words, <em>the exponential of a difference is the quotient of the exponentials</em>.
	</p>
</identity>

<identity xml:id="pattern-exp-exp">
	<title>Composing exponentials</title>
	<p>
		For positive base <m>a</m>,
		we have <me> {(a^u)}^v = a^{u v} </me>.
	</p>
</identity>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-exp-rate">
<title>Exponential rate</title>

<p>
Suppose we have a quantity experiencing exponential growth with the natural base,
so that <m>q(t) = e^t</m>
This means that that quantity at any moment is <m>e</m> times the quantity there was one time unit before,
similar to the <em>doubles every year</em> pattern in <xref ref="example-exp-doubling" />.
Consider forward and backward approximations of the rate of change for this function.
<md>
	<mrow> \ddt{q} \approx \slope{q}{t} \amp = \frac{q(t + \change{t}) - q(t)}{\change{t}} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = \frac{e^{t + \change{t}} - e^t}{\change{t}} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = \frac{e^t \cdot e^{\change{t}} - e^t}{\change{t}} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = e^t \cdot \frac{e^{\change{t}} - 1}{\change{t}} </mrow>
</md>.
So it appears we will have <me> \ddt{e^t} = a e^t </me>
where <me> a = \lim_{\change{t} \to 0} \frac{e^{\change{t}} - 1}{\change{t}} </me>.
Use the Sage cell below to investigate this limit by trying different small values,
both positive and negative,
for the time duration <m>\change{t}</m>
(represented by <c>dt</c> in the Sage cell).
</p>

<sage>
	<input>
		dt = 0.1
		a = (e^dt - 1) / dt
		print("a is approximately", a)
	</input>
	<output>a is approximately 1.05170918075648</output>
</sage>

<p>
So it appears that a quantity experiencing exponential growth with the natural base will have a rate-of-change function that also experiences exponential growth.
This is what makes exponential growth so great for your bank account but so terrible for the spread of a virus.
</p>

<p>
What if our quantity experiencing exponential growth is modelled using an exponential function with a different base?
Then, as in <xref ref="pattern-exp-horiz-scale" />,
we can instead model the quantity using some transformation of the natural exponential function:
<me> q(t) = e^{c t} </me>.
Let's again investigate the derivative by approximating with average rates of change.
Using a similar calculation to our earlier one,
we have
<me> \ddt{q} \approx e^{c t} \cdot \frac{e^{c \change{t}} - 1}{\change{t}} </me>,
so that <me> \ddt{e^t} = a e^{c t} </me>
where this time <me> a = \lim_{\change{t} \to 0} \frac{e^{c \change{t}} - 1}{\change{t}} </me>.
Again use the Sage cell below to investigate this limit by trying different small values,
both positive and negative,
for the time duration <m>\change{t}</m>
(represented by <c>dt</c> in the Sage cell).
Try it for different values of <m>c</m> as well
(we have entered <c>c = 5</c> for an initial investigation).
</p>

<sage>
	<input>
		dt = 0.1
		c = 5
		a = (e^(c * dt) - 1) / dt
		print("a is approximately", a)
	</input>
	<output>a is approximately 6.48721270700128</output>
</sage>

<p> Your Sage investigations above for different values for <m>c</m> hopefully led to the following universal pattern. </p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-exp-deriv">
	<title>Derivative of exponential functions</title>

	<p>
	We have <me> \ddt{e^{c t}} = c e^{c t} </me>.
	In particular, <me> \ddt{e^t} = e^t </me>.
	In other words,
	the natural exponential function is its own derivative.
	</p>

</identity>

<p>
The property of the natural exponential function expressed in <xref ref="pattern-exp-deriv" /> is extremely important,
and in fact is unique to the exponential function.
For that reason, this property will be crucial in helping us solve differential equations.
</p>

<example>
	<title>Solving radioactive decay</title>
	<p>
	Let's return to the differential equation
	<me> \ddt{q} = - k q(t) </me>
	from <xref ref="example-models-radioactive-decay" />.
	<xref ref="pattern-exp-deriv" /> tells us that <m>q(t) = e^{-k t}</m> is a solution:
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\mathrm{LHS} \amp = \ddt{q}
			\amp
			\mathrm{RHS} \amp = -k q(t)
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp = \ddt{e^{-k t}}
			\amp
			\amp = -k e^{-k t}
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = -k e^{-k t} </mrow>
	</md>.
	But using <xref ref="pattern-deriv-scale" />,
	we can verify that <m>q(t) = A e^{-k t}</m> is also a solution for every constant value <m>A</m>.
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\mathrm{LHS} \amp = \ddt{q}
			\amp
			\mathrm{RHS} \amp = -k q(t)
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp = \opddt (A e^{-k t})
			\amp
			\amp = -k (A e^{-k t})
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp = A \ddt{e^{-k t}}
			\amp
			\amp = A (-k e^{-k t})
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = A (-k e^{-k t}) </mrow>
	</md>.
	In fact,
	the expression <me> q(t) = A e^{-k t} </me>
	represents the general solution to this differential equation,
	where the parameter <m>A</m> represents the <em>initial amount</em>:
	<me> q(0) = A e^{-k \cdot 0} = A \cdot 1 = A </me>.
	</p>
</example>

<p>
In the scaled exponential function <m>q(t) = e^{c t}</m>,
the constant <m>c</m> is called the <term>rate constant</term>,
While <m>c</m> represents a horizontal scale factor of the quantity function <m>q(t)</m>,
we see from <xref ref="pattern-exp-deriv" /> it ends up also vertically scaling the rate-of-change function <me> \ddt{q} = c e^{c t}</me>.
It also represents the proportionality constant for a differential equation
<me> \frac{dq/dt}{q(t)} = \frac{c \cancel{e^{c t}}}{\cancel{e^{c t}}} = c </me>.
</p>

</section>

